            <fr:title text="Boolean valuations: verum and falsum">Boolean valuations: verum and falsum</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>     Finally, verum and falsum.
    These don't really have great natural-language equivalents.
    But the idea is pretty simple: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top ]]></fr:tex> is meant to be like the truest possible thing, MAXIMUM TRUE; and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> is meant to be like the falsest possible thing, MAXIMUM FALSE.</html:p>
            <html:p>What do we need to specify about these?
    Well, like with any connective, we need to say how to determine a value for any sentence with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top ]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> as its main connective, given values for all its components.
    And: sentences with nullary connectives as their main connectives have <html:em>no</html:em> components; these sentences are just the connectives themselves.
    </html:p>
            <html:p>
    So we need to give values for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top ]]></fr:tex> and for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> to take on every Boolean valuation.
    Given their intended interpretations, the choice is clear.
    For any Boolean valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> at all, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\top ) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\bot ) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>For uniformity, we can put these in "tables":</html:p>
